{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_hooloovoo_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280656872/1921011401/0254.xml":{"full_text":"THE EVENING STAB,\nWith Sunday Moraine Edition.\nWASHINGTON, D. C.\nFRIDAY....... Janu.ary 14, 1921\nTHEODORE W. NOTES... .Editor\n;The Evening Star Newspaper Company\nBusiness Office. 11th St. and Pennsylvania Ave.\nNew York Office: Tribune Building.\nChicago Office: First National Bank Building.\nBoropean Office: 3 Regent St., London, England.\nThe Evening Star, with the Sunday morning\nedition, is delivered by carriers within the city\nat 60 cents per month; daily only. 43 cents per\nmonth; Sunday only. 20 cents per month. Orders\nmay be sent by mail, or telephone Main\n5000. Collection ia made by carriers st the\nead of each month.\nRate by Mai]?Payable in Advance, j\nMaryland and Virginia.\njjauy ana aunaay. .1 yr., ss.tu: 1 mo., vuc\nDaily only 1 yr., $6.00; 1 mo.. 60c\nSunday only 1 yr.. $2.40; 1 mo.. 20c\nAll Other States.\nDally and Sunday. 1 yr., $10.00; 1 mo.. 85c\nDaily only 1 yr.. $7.00; 1 mo.. 60c\nSunday only 1 yr.. $3.00: 1 mo.. 26c\nGen. Crowder's First Eeport.\nGen. Crowder's investigations in.'\nCuba, have led him to put the responsibility\nfor present conditions in the\nisland largely on the courts. They\nh*vo been slow about handling contested\nelection cases, with the result\nthat the legislative power is threatened\nwith paralysis in the near future.\nThis may be said to complete the\nisland's difficulties.\nThe politicians have always been\nmore or less under charges. They\nwork under high pressure. They are\nmen of warm, temperament, and somewhat\nexplosive. They run overmuch\nto oratory; and that does not make\nfor practical results.\nThe financial affairs of the island\nare showing the difficulties that pre\nvail elsewhere?everywhere else. They\nare all snarled up. Both business and\nplanting circles are depressed, and\nuncertain as to the future. The most\nexperienced men are at a loss about\nlaying a further course, and watch\nins their steps closely.\nThus this indictment of the courts\nleaves little to hope for unless the\ntrouble somewhere along the line can\nbe speedily remedied. With the polifjn\na 'state of excitement over\na disputed national election, the business\nmen and the planters in a fog\nabout the future, and the courts failing\nto function promptly, conditions\nin Cuba must be in a grave way.\nIntervention in the circumstances\nwould impose a heavy responsibility\non us, and just now we are long on\nresponsibilities. -We have already\nquite as many as are desirable.\nYp TTanlintr and the Snn+li\nMr. Harding and the south have\nestablished, and are supporting, very\npleasant relations.\nAt Chicago, when the supreme moment\ncame in the convention, the\nsouth gave Mr. Harding some valuable\nassistance, and shared in the\nhonor of his nomination.\nIn the campaign she invited him\nto visit her, and he accepted the invitation.\nIn Kentucky, in Missouri,\nin Tennessee, in West Virginia and\ntn Maryland his receptions were enthusiastic\nand his audiences enormous\ntin size.\nSi'*\nOn election day Missouri, Tennessee,\nWest Virginia and Maryland\nplumped for him by large pluralities.\nMissouri going over the hundred thousand\nmark, while Kentucky reduced\nthe normal democratic plurality from\nforty thousand to four thousand.\nx- ux tvoif oiicr uio otreuuirany 01\nthe campaign, Mr. Harding selected\nTexas, and was welcomed to the state\nby the governor, and. a great display\n'p? cordiality on the part of the people.\nHe is now on the eve of a visit to\nFlorida, where he will rest from his\nlabors in conferring about policies\nand cabinet places, and prepare his\ninaugural address.\nThe south liked Arthur, McKinley,\nRoosevelt and Taft, and gave them\nevidences of her good will. But her\nmanifestations toward Mr. Harding\nhave probably exceeded in warmth\nany display of feeling she has hither*to\nshown toward any republican leader;\nand It may be that in office his\ncourse will please'her to the point of\nincreasing the republican strength\nwithin her borders.\nThe plan originating in Norfolk.\nVa., and known as the \"Norfolk idea,\"\nprovides that when a factory closes\norganized labor shall buy up the plant\nand run it. It is proposed to extend\nthe operation of the idea and some\nnovel experiences may arise which\nwill enable the man who signs the pay\n^eQ to realise the anxieties of the man\n'who baa to assemble the funds.\nThe diplomatic situation in Athens\nhas made the question of \"a (quiet\nhmMIh#' mas Krtn O lilcorraaa^ ?v? */V?A I\nroyal family one of more seriousness\ntViAT^ twyl.\nThe German rolice have born forbidden\nto wear monocles. This cannot\nbe regarded as a very Important\nstep Id disarmament.\n\nSmoking in the Offices.\nA Ml is to be introduced in Congress\nto prohibit smoking in all government\nbuildings in Washington.\nThis is .inspired by the recent fire in\nthe Commerce building, in whil-li some\nirreplaceable records were destroyed\nin' consequence of a blaze in the basement\nwhich; it is believed, was started\nby a carelessly flung cigarette\nstump. It has born'Erroneously stated\nthat this fire originated among shavings\nin the ifarpenter shop. In truth,\nthe blaze began at a considerable distance\nfrom the shop. Nevertheless,\nit did start somewhere and presumably\naa a result of carelessness. Burning\ncigars and cigarettes, particularly\nthe latter, are a prolific cause of fires,\nand the prohibition against smoking in\nrho departments is a logical suggestion\na$ long as there is so much recklessness\nIn the handling of these-dangerous\nmaterials. Apart from any\nother consideration, of good taste or\ncomfort, some restriction of smoking\nwould seem to be necessary as a\nmeans of safeguarding tho public\nproperty, especially o.? long as it re.\nmains exposed tb destruction in flroinviting.buildings\nand in flimsy combustihle\nshelving.\nBut It is one thing to prohibit smokand\nanother thins to enforce the\nway they will probably do it sooner\nor later. The only real safeguard is to\nfind them and lock them up or execute\nthem as murderers. These people are\nenemies of society and should be exterminated.\nBut it is a far cry to\nf|\ntheir identification and capture.\nTet it is rather strange that after\nBevcral years of persistent work in\nthe purlieus and slums where mur- p\nSerous radicalism festers the federal T\nand state police should not know just\nwho is doing this plotting. The country\nhas had several demonstrations\nDf their existence. There were the socalled\n\"Gimbel\" bombs, sent to vari- p\nous parts of the country in the wrappings\nof a New York department\nstore. There was the simultaneous\nexplosion of bombs in this city and P\nprohibition. Sometimes the very ban\nput. upon smoking on the score of dan-\nger leads to a greater danger because I\nthose seeking to violate the rule will 1\ngo into out-of-the-way places to in- i\ndulge in surreptitious smokes, and\nthere is where fires are most easily\nstarted and where they get the best\nheadway. Furthermore, the surrepti- i\ntious smoker Is apt to drop his glow- 1\niiig \"butt\" in a hurry if he thinks he i\nis in danger of detection. Perhaps it i\nwould be a good plan as long as smoking\nis such a universal habit to set 1\napart a room in every department or i\nbureau where smokers might congre-\ngate and indulge themselves at the\nrest periods which have become a\nfeature of most of the routine in most j\nof the offices. The government could i\nwell afford to spare such a room in\neach building, as at least a partial in- 1\nsurance against fire. 1\nm i 1\nFarmers' \"Strike'' a Failure. 1\nReports from the Minneapolis dis-\n?:u: a\nuii.1 unu unin IIIUUIIK dliu glclinhandling\ncenters indicate that the\nprogram of western and northwestern\nfarmers to hold their wheat for $3 a\nbushel has pretty well petered out.\nThe \"strike\" of the wheat growers\nhas met the fate of other movements\nwhich have set themselves up as dehors\nof economic laws. It has failed.\nThe heart was taken out of the\nfarmers' strike when the Bank of 1\nNorth Dakota, a state institution or- 2\nn\nganized by the Non-Partisan League,\nadvised the growers to abandon their c\n$3 a bushel program and to liquidate\ntheir wheat holdings in an orderly J\nway. It was only another instance\nof theory coming into collision with\npractice, with theory getting the 1\nworst of it. Managers of the North a\nDakota Bank were leaders in the Non-\nPartisan League movement, and it is\nto be presumed they subscribed to 1\nthe socialistic and paternalistic ten- t\nets of that organization. But when 1\nthey became bankers they found that\nfacts were the things with which they\nhad to deal, and it often happens that a\niduie uavc oiiwii icgifiu jui injuries.\nNow, if some of the other interests\nwhich persist in trying to maintain d\ninflated prices in a deflated market t\nwill profit by the lesson the wheat\ngrowers have learned, the process of\nprice leveling will be hastened and\nthe return of prosperity speeded.\nSome are quick to learn, and with\nothers it is a slow and painful process. a\nBut eventually even the dullest man\ndiscovers that he cannot hold him- p\nself up by his own boot straps. And t\nthat, in effect, is what is being at-\ntempted by those who are trying to\nmaintain the price levels of a year\nago.\nt!\nA Cabinet Job. a\nThe members of Mr. Harding's offi- 1\ncial family are going to be extremely P\nbusy men. Every one of them will a\nhave his hands full from the day he ii\ntakes office, and every day, from morn\ntill eve, and then some. tl\nTake the Secretary of State, with ii\nour foreign affairs to be adjusted to 1\nnew conditions everywnere; tne sec- a\nretary of the Treasury, with our\nfinancial affairs greatly complicated;\nthe Secretary of the \"Navy, with our\nnaval affairs of interest fa all \"the\nworld; the Secretary of War, with\nour military affairs changed by the\nworld war.\nAnd so on down the line. Every\ndepartment of the government will\nshow not only an increase of business, P\nbut business of new kinds, and hence\nwill tax both the mental and the\nphysical resources of its chief. He\nwill have to be up and about early tl\nand late, and on the Job unceasingly.\nBut this does not daunt men of P\nambition. The very size of the order\nis a sort of lure. They are willing,\neven eager, to 'sign up\" for the servitude.\nThey want to bear a hand in <j\nwork so difficult and important, and q\nat a time when an American official n\nof high class may hope for more than 0\nnational fame. p\nMr. Harding has a fine field to\nchoose from in filling his cabinet\nchairs. More names are probably presented\nfor his consideration than the\npublic is advised of; and when the\nresult of the drawing is announced\nthere may be a surprise or two.\nA\nAfter what the balloon boys did in c\nfighting perils and hardship, any\ntransient antagonisms among themselves\nare entitled to very little at- A\ntention.\nIA\nfilm manager says that within\nten years people will pay $5 a seat for\npictures. This is a ray of sunshine\nin an atmosphere of threatened hard\ntimes.\nSteamship men assort that news of\nunemployment in America is retarding\nimmigration. There are circum- 1\nstances under which a slight unpopularity\nmay be an asset.\nCertain coal transactions are suspected\nof having developed an exag- 0\nger'ated efficiency in the art of salesmanship.\nS\nh\nAn argument over a law is not con-\neluded until the means of enforcing t\nit are fully provided for.\nBomb Threats.\nSpecial police precautions have been k\ntaken in Philadelphia and New York t\nagainst the possibility of bomb outrages\nwhich have been threatened.\nInformation received by the public\nauthorities .in both cities has led to\nthe belief that explosions are planned\nto'take place within a short time, aiming\nat the destruction of public buildings,\nbanks, churches and the offices\nof leading financiers. Some anonymous\nletters have come, and In view\nof the tragedy of September 16 last, in\nWall street, of which a warning .was\nreceived but not heeded, the police\nof both cities are now talcing ho 1\nchances, but are thoroughly covering t\nall ground of possible attack.\nIt Is Impossible, of course, to Insure t\nabsolutely against a crime of this\ncharacter. The very fact that an- 1\nnouncement has been made that pre-\ncautions have been taken win probably\ndrive off the radicals, who will\nseek another time as more propitious.\nIf they have it in their hearts to de- I\nstroy property take lives In this i\nelsewhere, the local one destroying\nthe assassin himself. There was then\nthe Wall street explosion of last September.\nNobody has ever been iden- g\ntified in connection with these out- lr\nrages and they remain today mys- t!\neries. h\nol\nIf the federal secret service is in a\nno-thoroughfare regarding these fl\ncriminal activities it should frankly\nicknowledge the fact.\nbi\nb<\nThe Philippines.\nE. Finley Johnson, associate justice ti\n)f the Suoreme Court of the Philin- st\n>ines, is en route home on a visit, d<\nuid while in the country will call on er\ndr. Harding: and report as to present th\nconditions in the archipelago.\nIn an interview, given at Honolulu, e\\\ndr. Justice Johnson said that the y<\n'Moros of the Philippines never will 0j\nlubmit to Filipino Christian domina- N\nion, and further trouble between them\nmd native constabulary forces in Jolo th\ns to be expected.\" Jjs\nContinuing, the justice expressed m\nhis opinion: se\n\"The Moros are beginning to realize J*\nhat the Americans no longer are\nooking after them. The trouble pr\niown there is just beginning. There JH,\nrill be more of it and plenty of it.\nVhat the Moros want is American\n.dministration by Americans, and un- h\ness they get it they are going to\nause trouble.\"\nThe nnestinn of Amerlran vnth. \"f\nrawal from the Philippines, leaving\nhe natives to establish a government\nf their own, will probably not be m\naken up at this session of Congress, jg\nut is very likely to come before the w<\new Congress at its first regular ses- tl<\nion. As is known. President Wilson cc\nnd Gov. Gen. Harrison, his appointee, at\noth favor the proposition of indeendence,\nand there is an organiza- w\nion of prominent Filipinos working fy\nor its adoption. p<\nOn the other hand, there are influ- m\nCC\nntial men both in this country and\ni the Philippines who do not think w\ntie present a propitious time for such\nventure in that quarter of the world, pi\n\"hey doubt If the Filipinos are as yet M\nrepared to take over their affairs\nnd guarantee stability to a republic g;\na the orient. b<\nT\nMr. Harding is not committed in a.\nhe matter, nor is his party, except\n1 the most general way and terms.\n'hey have made no pronouncement d?\nto when, or bow.\nw\ni i ?????i n 8?\nW\nPathos employed by coal interests tc\nn impressing on the general attenlort.\ntheir sad situation arouses no p<\nympathy in the breast of Senator j\"?\n!alder. He is a \"hard audience\" who\noes not believe in wringing tears as f?\nrell as dollars from a kind-hearted\nublic. re\nm\n1 1 ft\nThe arrangements contemplate an u]\ntauguration in the open air unless\nhe climate forbids. The inauguration Je\nreather prophet has never been any\narticular friend of the innocent bytander.\n1\nt?\nw\nThe belligerent young balloonists\necided to patch up their personal ?u\nuarrels in time to prevent them from\necessarily becoming incidents of their tu\nfflcial interviews with the Navy De- A,\not\nartment. la\nin ofl\nSHOOTING STARS. b>\n?_cil\nva\nBT PHILANDER JOHNSON. la\nha\nBirds and Feathers. ?or\nm ostrich grew a feather fine, or\nAs is the bounden duty\n>f every bird who may incline Ol\nUnto a sense of beauty. 1\nmi\nm African traveler plucked the bird, gfj\nIts protest quite neglecting; su\nle merely chuckled as he heard\nIts tones of grief affecting. bo\nla\nl lady bought and wore the plume, ah\nHer pride of heart to nourish,\nihe thought it proper to assume\nThe feathers' fancy flourish.\nmd all admired the graceful swing, jj*\nAs round her smiles she spread it. hi\n*he ostrich did the work, poor thing! T1\nThe lady took the credit. Pr\nto\nAl\nSimplification. at\n\"Do you favor changing the date\nf inauguration?\"\n\"Not as much as I did.\" replied to\nlenator Sorghum. \"The ceremonials n<\nlave become so simplified that they\nnay eventually attract no greater d<\nhrongs than a meeting of the elec- Pi\noral college.\"\ntil\nKnocking. hi\n\"Wc will have an old-fa^hioncd\nmocker on the door,\" said the archi- w\nect. cc\n\"Don't do it,\" replied Mr. Growcher. P'\n'A natural born knocker can work\nast enough without providing him tli\nelth any mechanical facilities.\" in\nc?\nsi\nI'ps and Downs. tli\nInauguration fills life's cup\nWith sad experi ences.\nWe must forego the cutting up, le\nAnd cut down the expenses.\nConfusion in the Calendar. le\n\"Since putting my mind on plans\n'or the inauguration I am getting alf C8\nnixed up in my dates.\" 1 di\n\"But the plana for the lnauguraJon\nwere suddenly called off.\" It1\n\"That's the explanation. March\nfourth this year seems like the First\n>f April.\"\nifc' o,\nJud Tunklns says a bird thm-caa\nting and won't alng must be made to w:\nring?but how are you going to w.\n\nEditorial Digest\nToo Many Congressmen.\nIf Congress, in voting for the new\n^apportionment measure, and thus\ndeling forty-eight members to its\nody, is following the will of the\neople, then the newspapers of the\nountry do not reflect public opinion,\nhe majority of the press, even jourais\nin states whose population inrease\nwould entitle them to added\nepresentation at the Capitol, are aparently\nunited in the belief that\nhere are \"too many representatives\"\now. Few, however, see any hope ot\nhe development of an attitude on the\nart of our lawmaking body which\nlight persuade it to reduce its memership.\nA few voices are raised in rebuttal\nf the \"unwieldinees\" charge. The\nyracuse Herald (independent), for\nislanoe. calls attention to the fact\ntat \"the British house of commons\nas 670 members and the French\ntamber of deputtes not far from 600,\"\nA frankly sectional viewpoint is re.\nected in the New Orleans States\nlemocratic): \"The decision to in ease\nthe membership and to keep\nle population basis will naturally\ne welcomed in the south, for it may\na taken to mean that at least during\nle present administration there will\nno effort to curtail the representaon\nof this section arid weaken its\nrength in Washington and in presi.\n?ntial elections.\"\nThe Houston Chronicle (independit)\nholds a similar view, but grants\ntat \"the time will come\" when the\nembership in the House \"must be\n:ld stationary.\" That time, how'er,\nit is sure \"has hardly arrived\"\nit. But this view cannot be taken\nI representative either of the south\nof the nation, for the Charleston\news and Courier (democratic), after\nicu^jng republican leaders of insinrity\nin their economy talk, declares\nat instead of a larger House, \"oneilf\"\nthe present body would be \"inlitely\nmore effective as a lawmaking\norganization.\" This feeling\nems to be general and the Tacoma\n(dger's (independent) statement\nat \"congressmen, like dollars, deeciate\nin value when they are\nultiplied\" finds a counterpart in the\nin Antonio Kxprcss (independent\nimocratic).\nThe economy argument is taken up\nr many newspapers, among them\ne Indianapolis News (independent),\nhich considers it doubtful that\norty-eight additional representaves\nare worth a million dollars a\n:ar to the country.\"\n\"Too large for efficiency,\" contents\nthe Providence Tribune (indeindent\nrepublican), though Rhode\nland would lose a representative\nere its size decreased or left statnary\nunder present population.\nBut many believe that no state\n>uld really suffer if the meraberlip\nof the House were reduced, for.\ni the Nashville Banner (independtt)\nputs it, \"none would be dealt\nith unjustly if the reduction was\n?neral, and based on population, as\nle law requires, but it would be un>pular\nfor any representative to perit\nthe loss of representation if he\n>uld prevent it.\"\nApparently Massachusetts, which\nill be a gainer under the present\nan, does not ieei tne giory is worm\nle cost. The Springfield Union (rejblican)\nsays: \"It is permissible for\nassachusetts to congratulate her;lf\nupon the fact that in the conressional\nreapportionment she will\ntin two representatives, but only\nicause she has gained in population\nlatively. Nothing is gained by such\nreapportionment that would not be\nlined l?y one leaving the House no\nrger than at present.\"\nThe Baltimore Sun (independent\nimocratic) feels similarly concerning\ns own state, for though Maryland\nill be allotted an additional repremtative,\nthe Sun believes that \"It\nould be much better foi\" Maryland\nlose three of its members it alsady\nhas. if the representatives of\nle other states were reduced proirtionately,\"\nand if \"the, public were\nsally alive to the importance\" of\nlis. it might be accomplished.\nHope for such a change must be de rred,\nhowever, the Mobile Register\nlemocratlc) points out. by recurring\nthe \"solid south\" argument, for\n^publicans think \"it would be a great\nistake at this time to throw a buck:\nof cold water over the so.uth; and\nudoubtedly, if there exists any subantial\nhope, of breaking up the\nilld south, th.elr thought on the subct\nis correct:\"\nThe Labor Press.\nin this age of propagandlsm labor\nno means overlooks its chances,\nithin a year the labor press, daily,\nsekly and monthly, ha\" multiplied\njfuuiicitiiuiia rapiuiy. ruoiiciiiiuna\npported. controlled and written\nrgely for union men and workers in\nneral are said today to number be'een\n1,200 aiVd 1,500 in this country,\nrecent analysis pronounces thirteen\nthese to be radical as well as probor\nin character. Over a hundred\nIcial trade union otgans are now iscd.\nOther labor weeklies are owned\nlocal organizations or labor counIs.\nand some arc published as prite\nenterprises. Only two or three\nbor dailies are printed. New York\n.8 the Call, a socialist paper, and\nobably the most important labor\nurnal in English. The Unlon-Recd\nof Seattle is said to have a circution\nof 40,000. Milwaukee has the\nader, Minnesota tne Daily Star and\ndahoma also supports a dailjh\nVow labor seeks to develop one or\nore press services. The Federated\ness, with a wire and mail service\nnt out from Chicago, is reported to\npply 100 newspapers and to have\ni ws bureaus in several American\nties and in Europe. Its executive\nard is made up of representative\nhor newspaper men.?Boston Herrt\n(independent republican).\n\"Real Pan-Americanism.\"\nThe recent visit of the Secretary of\nate. Mr. Bainbridge Colby, to Rio\ni Janeiro is referred to by Brazilian\nwspapers as \"a milestone on the\nghway of real pan-Americanism.\"\nte phrape is typical of the happy imession\nwhich the Secretary appears\nbe leading all along the Datin\nmerican tour, which he is making\nthe request of President Wilson and\ni the President's personal representee.\nThe steady growth of warm feeling\nward the Cnited States by her\nsighbors to the south is one of the\nsculiarly valuable accomplishments\nthe Wilson administration. A\ncade ago a number of (.hose relblics\nwere anything but well disised\ntoward us. Somehow they had\nnceived the idea that the great neon\nto the north, from whom they\nid taken their political inspiration,\nieir constitutional form3 and almost\nleir entire genius of government,\nas inimical to them. But with the\nlining1 of Woodrow Wilson to the\nesidency they began to acquire a\nsw attitude. One of his earliest olBal.\nor semi-ofticial. speeches assured\nlein that this nation coveted not an\nch of any neighbor's lapd; and how\ninvincing. how irresistibly perstigvc\nwas his tolerant, patient, sympaletic\npolicy toward hapless 